Integration tests for `ctx_verify::cli::run`'s two output modes (terse text vs `--json`), exercised through a `FakeRunner` that stubs subprocess execution entirely — no real `cargo`/`clippy`/`fmt` is invoked.

`FakeRunner` implements `Runner::run` by keying canned `CommandOutcome`s off the first CLI arg passed to the tool; an unmapped or `None`-mapped key yields `Err(CheckError::ToolMissing(key))`, so tests simulate "tool not found" by inserting `None`. The `render(args, map) -> Result<(bool, String), Box<dyn Error>>` helper parses argv via `Cli::try_parse_from`, runs `cli::run` against the fake runner, and returns the pass/fail bool plus captured stdout — errors propagate via `?` rather than panicking, keeping it usable outside a `#[test]` body.

Key coupling: asserts the exact terse-mode format contract — a bare `"pass\n"` on success, and on failure a `"FAIL: <check> (<n>)"` header followed by `"<file>:<line>  <code>: <message>"` diagnostic lines, truncated per `--max-diagnostics` with a `"… +N more"` tail. Also asserts terse output never leaks a `"status"` JSON key, while `--json` mode must produce a parseable object with `status: "pass"`. Diagnostic parsing expects clippy's `compiler-message` JSON-lines format (`reason`, `message.level`, `message.code.code`, `message.spans[].{is_primary,file_name,line_start,column_start}`) — if the real cargo/clippy JSON schema changes, this fixture format and the corresponding parser in the crate must be updated together.